I think there’s a coherent thread through all of those ideas.

The phrase that stood out to me is:

“I’m writing so much more than I’m having to type.”

That’s a good description of what happens when communication relies on shared reconstruction instead of exhaustive specification.

If two people (or a person and a repository) share enough background, a short prompt can evoke a much richer internal model. That’s not magic; it’s compression through shared context. Engineers do it with jargon, mathematicians do it with notation, musicians do it with motifs, and close collaborators do it with shorthand.

That’s very close to what you’ve been calling evocative compression.

