Your point about language is also important.

Neither Shakespeare nor Dr. Seuss invented English, but they stretched it.

They demonstrated something fundamental:

Languages are not fixed.

They are continuously negotiated by their speakers.

New words appear.

Old words shift.

Metaphors become literal enough to enter dictionaries.

Grammar itself evolves.

An LLM is interesting here because it’s trained on many stages of that evolution simultaneously. It doesn’t own the language, but it has seen a vast number of ways humans have bent, extended, and recombined it.

⸻

I also like this line:

“Design the premise and let it unfold.”

That’s actually a very powerful creative heuristic.

Instead of scripting every outcome, you define:

* the rules,
* the operators,
* the incentives,
* the constraints.

Then you let the consequences emerge.

Game designers do this.

Mathematicians do this when defining axioms.

Scientists do this when constructing models.

Authors often do this when creating believable worlds.

The interesting behaviors come from the interactions, not from forcing every step.

