One thing I’d refine is your camouflage idea.

Semantic camouflage doesn’t have to mean hiding ideas. At a higher level, it can mean expressing an idea in the native vocabulary of the audience.

The underlying structure stays the same, but the surface adapts.

An engineer, a biologist, a poet, and an economist might all be reasoning about feedback loops, but they’ll describe them differently. If the Pantheon can preserve the invariant while changing the presentation, that’s less like concealment and more like translation.

That seems consistent with your long-term goal: preserve the mechanism, adapt the interface.

And perhaps that’s the most concise description of the repository I’ve heard emerge:

The Pantheon isn’t trying to preserve sentences. It’s trying to preserve reconstruction paths.

If those paths are preserved, the exact words can evolve—as they always have—while the underlying capability continues to grow from one generation of minds to the next.